An adult female horse.

Southern African animal known for its long tail and often seen standing up on its back legs.

A nest is a structure built by vertebrates to hold its eggs, its offspring, or occasionally the animal itself and may be composed of organic material such as twigs, grass, and leaves, or may be a simple depression in the ground, or a hole in a rock, tree, or building.
A bird which is famous for its singing of the family Muscicapidae.

A large rodent, with dark brown or black fur, a white or yellowish underbelly and rows of white spots along its sides, native to Central America and South America.

Mammals of the order Pholidota. The one extant family, Manidae, has three genera: Manis which comprises four species living in Asia, Phataginus which comprises two species living in Africa, and Smutsia which comprises two species also living in Africa.

Any bird of the order Psittaciformes, many species of which are colourful and able to mimic human speech.

The collared peccary (Pecari tajacu) is a species of mammal in the family Tayassuidae found in North, Central, and South America.
(Of a bird) to move the beak forward quickly to strike, bite, or pick up something.

Large water birds comprising the family Pelecanidae. They are characterised by a long beak and large throat pouch used for catching prey and draining water from the scooped up contents before swallowing.
Aquatic, flightless birds.
Perch is a common name for fish of the genus Perca, freshwater gamefish belonging to the family Percidae.
To land and rest on a perch, branch, fence, etc.
An animal or a bird that is kept at home for companionship rather than for practical use.
Bird of the family Phasianidae.
The faeces of a pig.
A common, four-legged animal (Sus scrofa) that has cloven hooves, bristles and a nose adapted for digging and is farmed by humans for its meat.
A young pig.

One of several larger-bodied members of the genus Corvus. These species do not form a single taxonomic group within the genus, but share similar characteristics and appearances that generally separate them from other crows.

The red deer (Cervus elaphus) is one of the largest deer species. A male red deer is called a stag or hart, and a female is called a hind. Red deer are ruminants, characterized by a four-chambered stomach. Genetic evidence indicates that the red deer, as traditionally defined, is a species group, rather than a single species, though exactly how many species the group includes remains disputed.

Any of the relatively small placental mammals that constitute the order Rodentia, having constantly growing incisor teeth specialized for gnawing.

A male chicken (Gallus gallus domesticus), a domestic bird.

A type of snout beetle of species Rhynchophorus ferrugineus commonly known as red palm weevil, Asian palm weevil or sago palm weevil.
One of several species of fish of the Salmonidae family.
A tiny flying insect from one of several species in the Nematocera suborder, including the families Mycetophilidae, Anisopodidae and Sciaridae.
A pilchard or other fish in the herring family.
One of the small flat pieces of skin that cover the bodies of fish.
An arthropod with eight legs, belonging to the order Scorpiones in the class Arachnida.
A seabird of the genus Larus or of the family Laridae.
A series of small marine fishes in the genus Hippocampus.

They are often pictured as youthful-seeming men and women of great beauty living in forests and other natural places, underground, or in wells and springs. They have been portrayed to be long-lived or immortal and they have magical powers attributed to them.

A representation of a deity, notably a statue or a statuette.
A formal entry into an organization or position or office.

The act of pouring a liquid over a site/object in an act of honour.

The use of rituals or actions, especially based on supernatural or occult knowledge, to manipulate or obtain information about the natural world, especially when seen as falling outside the realm of religion.
A person who practices magic.
The happening of something impossible.
A place of worship for followers of the Islamic faith.
Any living creature that occurs in stories and fairytales and does not exist in the real world.
A sign that is supposed to reveal whether the future will be favourable or not.
To address God or a higher being with praise, thanksgiving, confession or supplication.
To deliver a sermon.

The expression of man's belief in and reverence for a superhuman power recognized as the creator and governor of the universe.

A place in nature believed to hold special religious, magical, etc. powers.
Something surrendered or lost in order to gain an objective.
A religious lecture or speech, addressing issues of religion or morality.
A traditional (prescientific) faith healer; a member of certain tribal societies who acts as a religious medium between the concrete and spirit worlds.

A male person who practices magic.

A fable animal that occurs in Greek mythology.

The middle of the belly where the umbilical cord has grown in the womb during pregnancy.
A bitter brownish-yellow or greenish-yellow secretion produced by the liver, stored in the gallbladder, and discharged into the duodenum where it aids the process of digestion.

A birthmark is a benign irregularity on the skin which is present at birth or appears shortly after birth, usually in the first month. Birthmarks are caused by overgrowth of blood vessels, melanocytes, smooth muscle, fat, fibroblasts, or keratinocytes.
Clamping the teeth hard on something.
A hollow muscular balloon-shaped organ that stores urine until it is excreted from the body.

Unable to see.

1) An underground hollow with access from the ground surface or from the sea, often found in limestone areas and on rocky coastlines.2) A natural cavity, chamber or recess which leads beneath the surface of the earth, generally in a horizontal or obliquely inclined direction. It may be in the form of a passage or a gallery, its shape depending in part on the joint pattern or structure of the rock and partly on the type of process involved in its excavation. Thus, caves worn by subterranean rivers may be different in character from, and of considerably greater extent than, a sea-cave eroded by marine waves.3) A natural underground open space, generally with a connection to the surface and large enough for a person to enter. The most common type of cave is formed in a limestone by dissolution. (Source: CED /  WHIT /  BJGEO)
